snippet.textDisplay: for anyone wondering how a nuclear bomb works: when a nuclear bomb is detonated the entire process begins with the design and assembly of a device that contains either uranium 235 or plutonium 239 both of which are fissile materials meaning they have the rare property that when their atomic nuclei are struck by a free neutron they can split apart in a process known as nuclear fission releasing a huge amount of energy along with more neutrons that can go on to trigger further fission events and in the case of a gun type uranium bomb like the one dropped on hiroshima a subcritical mass of uranium is rapidly fired into another subcritical mass using a powerful conventional explosive propellant bringing the two pieces together to form a supercritical mass where the density and arrangement of atoms make it overwhelmingly likely that incoming neutrons will collide with nuclei before escaping thus beginning an uncontrollable chain reaction and in the case of an implosion type bomb which is used for plutonium weapons and is far more efficient the fissile core is surrounded by a carefully shaped shell of high explosives arranged in what is called a lens configuration which ensures that when detonated the blast waves from all points around the sphere are timed perfectly to converge inward and compress the plutonium core to a much smaller volume thereby drastically increasing its density and making it supercritical and to ensure the reaction starts at precisely the right moment a small device known as a neutron initiator is placed in the center which emits a burst of neutrons exactly as maximum compression is reached so that the chain reaction begins at the peak of efficiency and in the split seconds that follow each fission event releases energy equivalent to roughly two hundred million electron volts which is tiny for one atom but unimaginably huge when multiplied by the trillions upon trillions of atoms undergoing fission almost simultaneously and the temperature at the core rises to tens of millions of degrees celsius hotter than the surface of the sun while pressures climb to levels not found anywhere naturally on earth creating a rapidly expanding sphere of plasma that emits blinding light intense heat and deadly radiation and the explosive force of this reaction produces a shockwave that moves faster than sound crushing buildings and vehicles and throwing debris through the air at lethal speeds and the heat flash is so intense that it can cause severe burns or ignite flammable materials at distances of many kilometers and people within a certain radius may be vaporized instantly while those farther away might suffer blindness from the light alone and the initial burst of radiation consisting mainly of gamma rays and neutrons is capable of passing through human bodies and damaging cells at the molecular level leading to radiation sickness burns and long term cancer risks and as the fireball rises it pulls in air from all directions creating powerful winds while simultaneously lifting massive amounts of dust soil and vaporized material high into the atmosphere where it condenses into radioactive particles that fall back to the ground as fallout which can contaminate vast areas and remain dangerous for years or decades depending on the isotopes present and the effects on human health include acute radiation syndrome in the short term as well as genetic damage and increased cancer rates in the long term and the environmental effects include sterilization of soil killing of plant and animal life contamination of water supplies and alteration of atmospheric conditions and in the case of a thermonuclear or hydrogen bomb which uses a fission bomb as a trigger an additional stage of reaction occurs where the intense heat and pressure from the initial fission explosion cause isotopes of hydrogen such as deuterium and tritium to fuse together releasing even more energy per unit mass than fission and producing explosions measured in megatons of tnt equivalent rather than kilotons meaning the destructive power can be hundreds or even thousands of times greater with blast radii capable of leveling entire cities and causing climate effects such as nuclear winter where soot and debris block sunlight and lower global temperatures potentially collapsing agriculture and threatening the survival of large populations meaning that the design detonation and aftermath of a nuclear bomb involve not only the most extreme concentrations of energy humans have ever unleashed but also consequences that can persist across decades and even centuries for ecosystems societies and the stability of the planet itself
